When studying all the African nations that gained their independence in the 1950s and 1960s, Mozambique’s struggle for liberation is considered to have been somewhat longer than the average, since it took 11 years to fully liberate the country (Kellaway 2008). Undeterred by the Portuguese, the people of Mozambique fought valiantly in order to gain it. This fight was a very special one, not just because the battle was harder compared to other African countries that successfully achieved independence; it earned the admiration of other African nations.
